<subSubSection id="BBA8BFBF178741843E2A54A832BD6C33" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="7E80872E24C502D8ED7851BB5E2E3E49" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A6A866B93432270A18406D6293064638" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
The studied male of 
<taxonomicName id="1015A49A879A9979C4A1991CE9D9103A" genus="S." lsidName="S. urmiensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" rank="species" species="urmiensis">
<emphasis id="3B2D64CAC92A7A1242D52D897D067AB6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">S. urmiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected in 1975. Although several collecting trips have been made by the first author and her colleagues in HMIM to Urmia and Ghasemlu since then, no 
<taxonomicName id="1B317B98DCEBAA5E7691D3CCCB2192CE" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1825" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Sitochroa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sitochroa" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FECBB28B2067C2BF1E11079C936399B1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">Sitochroa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens have been collected again from that locality till now. In spite of the superficial similarities among the single examined 
<taxonomicName id="8E26D0F1CB3688D80063EA2C75DD5FE5" genus="S." lsidName="S. urmiensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" rank="species" species="urmiensis">
<emphasis id="2D9C8FA2C45442EE8CA43DB16EAE0E4F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">S. urmiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and some other 
<taxonomicName id="BE24D36A9A7ADCDC385F3C93D240E5D9" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1825" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Sitochroa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sitochroa" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DF8ECECE515B702C9DE173CE1BDB378D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">Sitochroa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, the differences in the male genitalia are considerable and the species can easily be distinguished.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
